The world born from September 11
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th commemoration of the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, in the United States.
On that day, 19 terrorists had taken control of four civilian airplanes, launched two of the planes into the World Trade Center towers in New York, struck the Pentagon with a third, and then led a fourth plane to crash in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believe was the White House or another U.S. government building in Washington, D.C.
All the air pirates were from the Middle East, and 15 from Saudi Arabia.
All had been trained in Afghanistan, and four in American flight schools, as part of a planned, organized, and executed operation by Al-Qaida (the "base"), the terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
At the end of the day, 2,977 innocent men, women and children were mourned as killed, and more than 6,000 injured.
Most were Americans, although citizens from over a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
Many at the time feared that September 11 had ushered in an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, other attacks carried out by Al-Qaïda followed, including several bombings on Madrid trains in March 2004, then the attack carried out on London's public transport in July 2005.
Terrorists having pledged allegiance to the Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels Airport in March 2016, and plotted a series of lesser-scale attacks (often using vehicles to run over pedestrians).
Nevertheless, neither the United States nor any of its allies have ever suffered from attacks of comparable scale to those of September 11 – which are without parallel.
It is therefore worth asking: Beyond the immediate losses, what difference did September 11 make?
Has history changed, and if so, to what extent?
Many reasons explain why terrorists were unable to carry out other major attacks.
After the U.S. invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaida lost its sanctuary.
Almost all governments around the world have implemented control procedures making it more difficult for potential terrorists to access airports and airplanes.
States have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities in order to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, terrorism being one of the rare areas in which states often at odds are willing and ready to work together to a significant extent.
There is also now a broad consensus around what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes – as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments cannot make a distinction between terrorists and those who provide them sanctuary and support.
The era where individuals and groups willing to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as fighters for freedom is over.
It is not to say that terrorism has ceased to take the lives of tens of thousands of people every year.
Nonetheless, almost all attacks take place in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia within the context of current conflicts (mainly in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks of the 9/11 type against major powers.
Terrorism is becoming increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist organization's leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
Al-Qaïda, for example, survived the elimination of Bin Laden by U.S. special forces in Pakistan, nearly ten years after the 9/11 attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, with no resolution to the problem on the horizon.
The possibility of a new September 11 cannot be ruled out either, although the U.S. government has recently stated that the « most urgent terrorist threat » for the country exists domestically.
As the Provisional Irish Republican Army formulated after its failed attempt to assassinate British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984, « Today, we didn’t have luck, but remember that it only takes one chance.»
You will have to have it always.»
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists will get their hands on nuclear material, or manage to manufacture and use a biological or chemical weapon, in which case terrorism could determine the era.
For now, this is not the case.
September 11 nevertheless marked a turning point in history, with a profound impact on American foreign policy over the past 20 years.
Although the attacks did not lead to a global era of terrorism, they did indeed generate the famous global war on terror, with major consequences on the behavior of the United States around the world, the image of America in the eyes of the world, and the way in which many Americans eventually came to view their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
Shortly after the September 11 attacks, the United States presented a choice to the Taliban, who were then in control of the Afghan government: hand over the perpetrators of Al-Qaida, who were about to leave the country and were responsible for organizing the September 11 attacks, or risk losing their rule.
After the Taliban refused to hand over Al-Qaida leaders, U.S. intelligence and military forces collaborated with an loosely structured Afghan tribal confederation called the Northern Alliance to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of most of the country.
This control was never total, nor uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaida took refuge in the neighboring Pakistan, where they gradually regained strength and resumed their military operations against the government that had replaced them.
Meanwhile, the United States did not sufficiently work to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of sanctuary in Pakistan.
Instead, the United States strengthened its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, becoming essentially a partner of the government in its civil war.
At its peak, the United States' intervention in Afghanistan mobilized more than 100,000 American soldiers.
Over twenty years, the cost of the operations amounts to more than $2,000 billion, for more than 2,300 American lives lost, and several tens of thousands among the Afghans.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
The American presence deprived the Afghan government of a large part of its legitimacy, and sparked opposition to the United States, while the Taliban proved more persistent than the United States, which in 2020 had lost all will to fight in a conflict destined to end only in an indefinite stalemate.
The global war on terrorism also led the United States to go to war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have acted militarily had September 11 not occurred.
The attacks certainly reinforced his tendency to signal to the world that the United States was not, as President Richard Nixon had phrased during the Vietnam War, a « giant helpless and pitiful ».
This led some members of the administration (notably Vice President Dick Cheney) to refuse the risk of seeing terrorists seize weapons of mass destruction, which the Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein seemed to possess (which, according to most participants, was not the case).
Others intended to spread democracy in Iraq, then throughout the Middle East, considering that this endeavor was not only feasible, but would also make the region much less likely to produce terrorists and support them.
The war in Iraq, launched in March 2003, did not unfold as President Bush's administration and numerous members of Congress (including Joe Biden, then a senator) and global leaders who had supported it had hoped or anticipated.
The United States was not prepared for the majority of events to come.
Military victories initially allowed the removal of the government, but quickly gave way to widespread unrest and violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army and exclude many Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government jobs exacerbated an already chaotic situation.
More fundamentally, Iraq, like Afghanistan, demonstrated the limits of what military force can achieve at a reasonable cost and within reasonable timeframes.
In the end, the United States was forced to strengthen its military presence, bringing it to nearly 170,000 soldiers, in order to preserve the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability was achieved, but at a considerable cost.
The United States spent at least as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but for a much heavier human toll: over 4,000 American soldiers killed, a far greater number of wounded, and an explosion in the rate of suicide among American military personnel (both in Iraq and Afghanistan).
This total also excludes deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for whom estimates vary widely, but whose number is certainly in the hundreds of thousands.
The war in Iraq also weakened the United States in other respects.
No evidence has ever demonstrated Iraq's involvement in the September 11 attacks, and the United States' reputation suffered when the argument for a military intervention without UN approval – aimed at eliminating Saddam's weapons of mass destruction – was found to be based on no real foundation.
Images of American soldiers mistreating Iraqi prisoners further damaged the country's reputation.
Moreover, an Iraq at war with itself became synonymous with an Iran emerging as the most powerful country in the region (or one of the two most powerful if one considers Israel).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence over Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also proven to be two major strategic distractions.
While the United States was deeply involved in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking major powers and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance shifted against the United States, both in Europe and in East Asia, due to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia, as well as a stronger and more assertive China.
The global war on terrorism could not and did not provide the United States with a compass for its approach to foreign policy toward a renewed rivalry among great powers.
The wars fought in the aftermath of September 11 also had significant domestic consequences for the United States.
They shook the confidence of a country that had emerged from the Cold War as a historically unprecedented dominant power, and undermined the national unity that had surfaced immediately after the attacks.
The costs and failures associated with these wars have also fueled opposition to a major and enduring global role for the United States, giving rise to a new isolationist trend.
Similarly, this propensity for war, combined with the global financial crisis of 2007-2009 and its economic repercussions, seriously impacted American confidence in elites, thus stimulating the rise of a populist sentiment that, among other consequences, contributed to the rise of Donald Trump to power.
Today’s America is more divided than ever internally, and less and less willing to pursue this form of active foreign policy that characterized it since the end of World War II, and which has largely benefited Americans as well as many others.
In retrospect, we can now consider September 11 as a harbinger of what was to come: less the globalization of terrorism than the terrors of globalization.
The attacks sent the message that distance and borders mattered little in the global era.
Nothing remains local for very long anymore, whether it be terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis that originates from poor American financial management.
We are all currently facing a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since its emergence in China in December 2019.
Fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves that are devastating many regions of the world are the consequence of climate change, itself a cumulative effect of human activity that releases unsustainable amounts of heat-trapping greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
The era begun by recent events concludes a cycle, marking the 20th anniversary of the U.S. intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly ousted from power; in recent weeks, they have regained it just as easily.
It is too early to know whether the Taliban will resume their old habits by becoming once again a terrorist sanctuary, and whether terrorists around the world will take pride in their victory over America and its allies.
What we know, on the contrary, is that terrorism remains a characteristic of our world.
It will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible aspects of a globalization that itself determines it already.
